See manual_full_00_README.txt for the tier legend (NAV/STREAM/PYRUN/BLOCKED) before reading this file.

[BF-001-identity]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .
INPUT = "Hello, world!"
GOLD = "Hello, world!"
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$."}}
COMMENT=NAV. Same as curated-batch 100.

[BF-002-identity-precision]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .
INPUT = 0.12345678901234567890123456789
GOLD = 0.12345678901234567890123456789
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$."}}
COMMENT=NAV, same template as BF-001. Whether JFTL preserves the untruncated literal on pass-through is an engine/serializer question, not a template-syntax one.

[BF-003-identity-decnum-family]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = N/A
INPUT = N/A
GOLD = N/A
JFTL = N/A
COMMENT=N/A (compressed, see README): manual.yml's Identity section has 5 more examples (lines 399-417) all gated on jq's own `have_decnum`/`tojson`/big-integer-literal build flag -- e.g. "[., tojson] == if have_decnum then [...] else [...] end". These test jq's C-level --disable-decnum build option specifically; JFTL has no equivalent concept, so skipping rather than fabricating a meaningless port.

[BF-004-object-identifier-index]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .foo
INPUT = {"foo": 42, "bar": "less interesting data"}
GOLD = 42
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$.foo"}}
COMMENT=NAV. Same as curated-batch 101.

[BF-005-object-identifier-index-missing]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .foo
INPUT = {"notfoo": true, "alsonotfoo": false}
GOLD = null
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$.foo"}}
COMMENT=NAV. Same as curated-batch 102.

[BF-006-object-index-bracket]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .["foo"]?
INPUT = {"foo": 42}
GOLD = 42
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$.foo"}}
COMMENT=NAV. NOTE: the standalone "Object Index: .[<string>]" section has no examples of its own in manual.yml -- this is the verbatim example borrowed from the neighboring "Optional Object Identifier-Index" section (its 3rd example) since it's the only place manual.yml actually exercises bracket-string indexing. Navigation.md's quoted-key form ["foo"] and bare-key form .foo resolve identically here.

[BF-007-optional-object-index]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .foo?
INPUT = {"foo": 42, "bar": "less interesting data"}
GOLD = 42
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$.foo"}}
COMMENT=NAV. jq's `?` suppresses type errors; Navigation.md already makes all navigation null/MISSING-safe by default, so the `?`-suffixed and plain forms map to the identical template. Same input as BF-004.

[BF-008-optional-object-index-nonobject]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .foo?
INPUT = {"notfoo": true, "alsonotfoo": false}
GOLD = null
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$.foo"}}
COMMENT=NAV, same template as BF-007.

[BF-009-optional-index-array-input]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = [.foo?]
INPUT = [1,2]
GOLD = []
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= ([_['foo']] if isinstance(_, dict) and 'foo' in _ else [])"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, revised, lower confidence than most: type-checks before indexing since Python has no null-safe .foo-on-a-list concept. Sidesteps curated-108's array-literal-body question by building the collect result in Python.

[BF-010-array-index]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .[0]
INPUT = [{"name":"JSON", "good":true}, {"name":"XML", "good":false}]
GOLD = {"name":"JSON", "good":true}
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$[0]"}}
COMMENT=NAV, same pattern as curated-batch 104.

[BF-011-array-index-out-of-range]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .[2]
INPUT = [{"name":"JSON", "good":true}, {"name":"XML", "good":false}]
GOLD = null
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$[2]"}}
COMMENT=NAV. Confirms Navigation.md's "out-of-range index -> MISSING" collapses to null at top-level output, same as BF-005/curated-102.

[BF-012-array-index-negative]
LEVEL=navigation
JQ = .[-2]
INPUT = [1,2,3]
GOLD = 2
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$[-2]"}}
COMMENT=NAV, same pattern as curated-batch 104b.

[BF-013-slice-array]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .[2:4]
INPUT = ["a","b","c","d","e"]
GOLD = ["c", "d"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _[2:4]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, same pattern as curated-batch 104c.

[BF-014-slice-string]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .[2:4]
INPUT = "abcdefghi"
GOLD = "cd"
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _[2:4]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Python slicing works identically on str and list, so same template as BF-013 -- a nice free win if the escape-hatch guess is right.

[BF-015-slice-open-start]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .[:3]
INPUT = ["a","b","c","d","e"]
GOLD = ["a", "b", "c"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _[:3]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, same family as BF-013.

[BF-016-slice-open-end-negative]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = .[-2:]
INPUT = ["a","b","c","d","e"]
GOLD = ["d", "e"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= _[-2:]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN, same family as BF-013.

[BF-017-array-iterator]
LEVEL=navigation
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .[]
INPUT = [{"name":"JSON", "good":true}, {"name":"XML", "good":false}]
GOLD = [{"name":"JSON", "good":true}, {"name":"XML", "good":false}]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {"var": "x"}, "body": "$."}}
COMMENT=STREAM, same pattern as curated-batch 105.

[BF-018-array-iterator-empty]
LEVEL=navigation
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .[]
INPUT = []
GOLD = []
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {"var": "x"}, "body": "$."}}
COMMENT=STREAM, same template as BF-017 -- zero-iteration edge case, good regression test once foreach is real.

[BF-019-foo-iterator]
LEVEL=navigation
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .foo[]
INPUT = {"foo":[1,2,3]}
GOLD = [1,2,3]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$.foo"}}
COMMENT=CORRECTION to curated-batch 106 (which I'd marked blocked): no foreach needed at all for a plain passthrough-iterate-nested-field case. $.foo resolves to the whole array as one item (Navigation.md), and OUT_FMT=STREAM unwraps that array for comparison -- same trick BF-017/105 used before I overcomplicated it with foreach. Foreach is only actually required when a per-item TRANSFORM has to happen during iteration (like BF-025/curated-107's ".name" projection), not for plain iteration.

[BF-020-object-value-iterator]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .[]
INPUT = {"a": 1, "b": 1}
GOLD = [1, 1]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= list(_.values())"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM, sidesteps the object-vs-array foreach-default question entirely: compute the values as a real array in Python, then let OUT_FMT=STREAM unwrap that array. Still don't know whether foreach itself auto-detects object input (see curated-batch 106's original concern), but this route doesn't need it.

[BF-021-optional-iterator]
LEVEL=SKIPPED
JQ = N/A
INPUT = N/A
GOLD = N/A
JFTL = N/A
COMMENT=SKIPPED, not fabricated: the ".[]?" section in manual.yml has no examples of its own (body text only). Not manufacturing one to keep this file a faithful "ALL test cases FROM the manual," per your ask -- happy to add a synthetic one if you want the coverage anyway.

[BF-022-comma]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .foo, .bar
INPUT = {"foo": 42, "bar": "something else", "baz": true}
GOLD = [42, "something else"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [_.get('foo'), _.get('bar')]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM, revised: build the fan-out as a Python list, OUT_FMT=STREAM unwraps it into jq's two separate outputs.

[BF-023-comma-mixed-scalar-iterator]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .user, .projects[]
INPUT = {"user":"stedolan", "projects": ["jq", "wikiflow"]}
GOLD = ["stedolan", "jq", "wikiflow"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [_.get('user')] + _.get('projects', [])"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM, revised. Same expression as TV-001, but this one streams (3 separate jq outputs, no enclosing [...]) so OUT_FMT=STREAM is set here where TV-001 didn't need it.

[BF-024-comma-index-list]
LEVEL=logic
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .[4,2]
INPUT = ["a","b","c","d","e"]
GOLD = ["e", "c"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= [_[4], _[2]]"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN+STREAM, revised.

[BF-025-pipe]
LEVEL=foreach
OUT_FMT=STREAM
JQ = .[] | .name
INPUT = [{"name":"JSON", "good":true}, {"name":"XML", "good":false}]
GOLD = ["JSON", "XML"]
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "foreach": {"var": "x"}, "body": "$.name"}}
COMMENT=STREAM, same pattern as curated-batch 107.

[BF-026-parenthesis]
LEVEL=logic
JQ = (. + 2) * 5
INPUT = 1
GOLD = 15
JFTL = {"main": {"$": true, "body": "$pyrun= (_ + 2) * 5"}}
COMMENT=PYRUN. Grouping/arithmetic, no native equivalent, straight Python translation.
